           SET
          -----
             *it is defined as unordered collection of various items enclosed with in a curly braces
             *not duplicated
             * immutable
             *no index
            
           Adding items
           s=set([1,2,3,4,5])
           s.add("HELLO")
           print(s)
           {1,2,3,HELLO,4,5}
           
           add multiple item in the set\
           s=set([1,2,3,4,5,6])
           s.update(["s","is","updated"])
           print(s)
           {1,2,'update',5,'is','s',20,25,30}
           
           removing item from set
         --------------------------
         
         s={1,2,3,4}
         s.remove(5)   #error
         s.dicard(5)

         s.pop()           
         s.clear()
         
         union
        -------
         *union operator -|
         *union function -union()
         eg: s1={"I","Abhi","Abhi"}
             s2={"I","Ram","Ram"}
             print(s1|s2)
             {'Abhi', 'I', 'Ram'}
             print(s1.union(s2))
             {'Abhi', 'I', 'Ram'}
             
          *intersection of two set
            print(s1&s2)
            {"I"}
            
         *Frozen sets 
               --frozen sets are the immutable form of the normal sets ie the items of the frozen set can not be changed

